        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Par&ugrave;m valet Virtus sine Occasione: aut Occasio sine Virtute.
                        Brutus, acerrimus opportunitatis persequenda[e] Dux; et novandarum rerum Auctor egregius. Singularia in omnem partem, 
                        notatu digniora: pra[e]sertim ubi respondet effectus, cum magnifico successu. Non est tutum, Leonem, aut Canem dormientem excitare: 
                        et Magistratus ostendit virum. Multa[e] politica[e], et sophistica[e] praxes pro, et contra, si intim&egrave; penetrentur. 
                        Vix usq[uam] plura tam paucis, pra[e]terq[uam] in Suetonii Ca[e]saribus; aut Aurelii Victoris; aut Juliani, qui ludens rem agit seriam; 
                        aut talium perpaucorum. Nam pla[e]riq[ue] non tam discursu longiores, qu&agrave;m effectu breviores.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Brutus"/>
                    <person name="Suetonius"/>
                    <person name="Aurelius Victor"/>
                    <person name="Julian"/>
                    <book title="De Vita Caesarum"/>
                    <book title="De Caesaribus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Virtue without opportunity has insufficient impact, and so does opportunity without virtue.
                Brutus was the strongest leader in pursuing opportunity, and an outstanding promotor of change. The details deserve keen attention in each respect, 
                especially where, with brilliant success, the result is correspondent. It is not safe to wake up a sleeping lion, or dog, and the magistrate reveals the man. 
                There are many clever policies for and against, if [only] they are profoundly investigated. There is hardly more anywhere in so few words anywhere, 
                except in Suetonius’ [Lives of the] Caesars, or in those of Aurelius Victor, and Julian, who discusses this serious subject playfully, 
                or in the biographies of a very few similar authors. For most not only provide a longer treatment, but also a shallower result.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
